      # Part (b):
      Part Content: Given that $\vec{a}=\begin{bmatrix}4 \\ -2 \\ -5 \\ 2\end{bmatrix}$, what is its length?;

      ## Response Area: 1

      (Secret) Expected Answer: 7;
      My Latest Submission: none made;
      No direct answer

      ## Worked Solution 1: 
      We can find the length of vector $\vec{a}$ using the dot product
;  ;
$$
|\vec{a}| = \sqrt{\vec{a} \cdot \vec{a}}
$$
;   ;
First, let's calculate the dot product of $\vec{a}$ with itself:
;   ;
$$
\begin{array}{rl}\vec{a} \cdot \vec{a} &= \begin{bmatrix}4  \\ -2 \\ -5 \\ 2\end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix}4  \\ -2 \\ -5 \\ 2\end{bmatrix} \\\\&= 4^2+(-2)^2+(-5)^2+2^2 \\\\ &= 49\end{array}
$$
;     ;
Now, we can calculate the length of $\vec{a}$:
;       ;
$$
\begin{array}{rl}|\vec{a}|&=\sqrt{\vec{a} \cdot \vec{a}} \\\\ &=\sqrt{49}  \\\\ &= 7\end{array}     
$$
;        ;
Therefore, the length of vector $\vec{a}$ is approximately 7 arbitrary units


      # [CURRENTLY WORKING ON] Part (c):
      Part Content: Given that $\vec{N}=\begin{bmatrix}3 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix}$, construct a new vector, $\vec{n}$ , that is pointing along the same direction but is of unit length;

      ## Response Area: 1

      (Secret) Expected Answer: 0.6,0.8;
      My Latest Submission: none made;
      No direct answer

      ## Worked Solution 1: 
      To construct a vector pointing in the same direction as $\vec{N}$ but with unit length, we need to normalize it. Normalising a vector involves scaling the vector with the reciprocal of its length.
;        ;
***

First, let's calculate the length of $\vec{N}$
;     ;
$$
\begin{array}{rl}|\vec{N}|&=\sqrt{\vec{N} \cdot \vec{N}} \\\\&= \sqrt{\begin{bmatrix}3  \\ 4\end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix}} \\\\&= \sqrt{3^2+4^2}\\\\&= \sqrt{25} \\\\ &= 5\end{array}
$$
;       ;
***
;      ;
Now, we can normalise $\vec{N}$ by multiplying it by the reciprocal of its length
;   ;
$$
\begin{array}{rl}\vec{n}&=\frac{1}{|\vec{N}|} \ \vec{N}\\\\ &=\frac{1}{5}\begin{bmatrix}3 \\ 4\end{bmatrix} \\\\ &= \begin{bmatrix}0.6 \\ 0.8\end{bmatrix}\end{array}
$$


      # Part (d):
      Part Content: Between the two vectors $\vec{U}$ and $\vec{W}$, which one of them has an orientation that is closer to $\vec{V}$?
;  ;
$$
\vec{U}=\begin{bmatrix}9 \\ -4 \\ -5 \\ 3\end{bmatrix} \quad \vec{W}=\begin{bmatrix}-4 \\ 7 \\ -2 \\ -5\end{bmatrix} \quad \vec{V}=\begin{bmatrix}3 \\ 9 \\ -1 \\ -2\end{bmatrix}
$$;

