      ## Worked Solution 1: Stupid but more conceptually involved method
      The dot product provides information about the alignment of two vectors. Intuitively, a larger dot product indicates a closer alignment between the vectors. However, the dot product is also influenced by the magnitudes of the vectors. To ensure a fair comparison of orientations, it is necessary to normalize the vectors involved ( we don't have to normalise $\vec{V}$ because its magnitude will influence both dot products to the same extent ). By normalising the vectors and then computing the dot product, we can accurately assess their relative orientations independent of their magnitudes.
;   ;
***
; ;
### Normalisation
; ;
We first have to find the length of each vector
; ;
$$
\begin{matrix}
\small\boxed{\begin{array}{rl}|\vec{U}|&=\sqrt{\vec{U} \cdot \vec{U}} \\\\&= \sqrt{\begin{bmatrix}9 \\ -4 \\ -5 \\ 3\end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix}9 \\ -4 \\ -5 \\ 3\end{bmatrix}} \\\\&= \sqrt{9^2+(-4)^2+(-5)^2+3^2}\\\\&= \sqrt{131}\end{array}}
&&
\small\boxed{\begin{array}{rl}|\vec{W}|&=\sqrt{\vec{W} \cdot \vec{W}} \\\\&= \sqrt{\begin{bmatrix}-4 \\ 7 \\ -2 \\ -5\end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix}-4 \\ 7 \\ -2 \\ -5\end{bmatrix}} \\\\&= \sqrt{(-4)^2+7^2+(-2)^2+(-5)^2}\\\\&= \sqrt{94}\end{array}}
\end{matrix}
$$
;  ;
***
; ;
We can then normalise them
; ;
$$
\begin{matrix}\boxed{\begin{array}{rl}\vec{u}&=\frac{1}{|\vec{U}|} \ \vec{U}\\\\ &=\frac{1}{\sqrt{131}}\scriptsize\begin{bmatrix}9 \\ -4 \\ -5 \\ 3\end{bmatrix} \end{array}} \quad \boxed{\begin{array}{rl}\vec{w}&=\frac{1}{|\vec{W}|} \ \vec{W}\\\\ &=\frac{1}{\sqrt{94}}\scriptsize\begin{bmatrix}-4 \\ 7 \\ -2 \\ -5\end{bmatrix} \end{array}}\end{matrix}
$$
; ;
***
; ;
### Dot Product
; ;
We can now compute the dot product between the normalised vectors and $\vec{V}$

$$
\begin{matrix}
\boxed{\begin{array}{rl}
\vec{u}\cdot\vec{V}&=
\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{131}}\scriptsize\begin{bmatrix}9 \\ -4 \\ -5 \\ 3\end{bmatrix}\right)•\scriptsize \begin{bmatrix}3 \\ 9 \\ -1 \\ -2\end{bmatrix}
\\\\
&=\frac{1}{\sqrt{131}}\left(\scriptsize\begin{bmatrix}9 \\ -4 \\ -5 \\ 3\end{bmatrix}•\begin{bmatrix}3 \\ 9 \\ -1 \\ -2\end{bmatrix}\right)
\\\\
&=\frac{1}{\sqrt{131}}\scriptsize[(9\cdot3)+(-4\cdot9)+(-5\cdot-1)+(3\cdot-2)]
\\\\
&≈-0.8737
 \end{array}}
\\\\
\boxed{\begin{array}{rl}
\vec{w}\cdot\vec{V}&=
\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{94}}\scriptsize\begin{bmatrix}-4 \\ 7 \\ -2 \\ -5\end{bmatrix}\right)•\scriptsize \begin{bmatrix}3 \\ 9 \\ -1 \\ -2\end{bmatrix}
\\\\
&=\frac{1}{\sqrt{94}}\left(\scriptsize\begin{bmatrix}-4 \\ 7 \\ -2 \\ -5\end{bmatrix}•\begin{bmatrix}3 \\ 9 \\ -1 \\ -2\end{bmatrix}\right)
\\\\
&=\frac{1}{\sqrt{94}}\scriptsize[(-4\cdot3)+(7\cdot9)+(-2\cdot-1)+(-5\cdot-2)]
\\\\
&≈6.4980
 \end{array}}
\end{matrix}
$$
;  ;
Comparing the magnitudes of $\vec{w}\cdot\vec{V}$  and $\vec{u}\cdot\vec{V}$, we find that $\vec{w}\cdot\vec{V}$ is larger than $\vec{w}\cdot\vec{V}$.
; ;
Therefore, the vector $\vec{W}$ has an orientation that is closer to $\vec{V}$.

      ## Worked Solution 2: Plugging in numbers
      To determine which vector, $\vec{U}$ or $\vec{W}$, has an orientation closer to $\vec{V}$ using the dot product-cosine formula
; ;
***
1.  **Calculate the dot products:**
    ; ;
    $$
    \vec{U}\cdot\vec{V}=(9 \cdot 3) + (-4 \cdot 9) + (-5 \cdot -1) + (3 \cdot -2) = -10 \\ \ \\  \vec{W} \cdot \vec{V} = (-4 \cdot 3) + (7 \cdot 9) + (-2 \cdot -1) + (-5 \cdot -2) = 63
    $$
    ; ;
    ***
2.  **Calculate the magnitudes:**
    ;  ;
    $$
    \begin{matrix}
    \small\boxed{\begin{array}{rl}|\vec{U}|&=\sqrt{\vec{U} \cdot \vec{U}} \\\\&= \sqrt{\begin{bmatrix}9 \\ -4 \\ -5 \\ 3\end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix}9 \\ -4 \\ -5 \\ 3\end{bmatrix}} \\\\&= \sqrt{9^2+(-4)^2+(-5)^2+3^2}\\\\&= \sqrt{131}\end{array}}
    &&
    \small\boxed{\begin{array}{rl}|\vec{W}|&=\sqrt{\vec{W} \cdot \vec{W}} \\\\&= \sqrt{\begin{bmatrix}-4 \\ 7 \\ -2 \\ -5\end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix}-4 \\ 7 \\ -2 \\ -5\end{bmatrix}} \\\\&= \sqrt{(-4)^2+7^2+(-2)^2+(-5)^2}\\\\&= \sqrt{94}\end{array}}
    \end{matrix}
    \\ \ \\
    \small\boxed{\begin{array}{rl}|\vec{V}|&=\sqrt{\vec{V} \cdot \vec{V}} \\\\&= \sqrt{\begin{bmatrix}3 \\ 9 \\ -1 \\ -2\end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix}3 \\ 9 \\ -1 \\ -2\end{bmatrix}} \\\\&= \sqrt{(3)^2+9^2+(-1)^2+(-2)^2}\\\\&= \sqrt{95}\end{array}}

    $$
    ; ;
    ;  ;
    ***
3.  **Calculate the cosines of the angles:**

    $$
    \cos(\theta_{\vec{U}\vec{V}}) = \frac{\vec{U}\cdot\vec{V}}{|\vec{U}|  |\vec{V}|} = \frac{-10}{\sqrt{131} \cdot \sqrt{95}}
    \\ \ \\ \ \\
    \cos(\theta_{\vec{W}\vec{V}}) = \frac{\vec{W}\cdot\vec{V}}{|\vec{W}|  |\vec{V}|} = \frac{62}{\sqrt{94} \cdot \sqrt{95}}
    $$
    ;  ;
    ***
4.  **Calculate and compare the angles**

    $$
    \theta_{\vec{U}\vec{V}}=\cos^{-1}\left(\frac{-10}{\sqrt{131} \cdot \sqrt{95}}\right)≈95.1^\circ
    \\ \ \\ \ \\
    \theta_{\vec{W}\vec{V}}=\cos^{-1}\left(\frac{62}{\sqrt{94} \cdot \sqrt{95}}\right)≈49.0^\circ
    $$

    Since $\theta_{\vec{W}\vec{V}}<\theta_{\vec{U}\vec{V}}$ , the orientation of $\vec{W}$ is closer to $\vec{V}$ then that of \$\vec{U}\$
